1
00:00:38,800 --> 00:00:40,836
Calling Cape Com. Cape Com?

2
00:00:40,960 --> 00:00:42,712
This is Jupiter 16.

3
00:00:42,840 --> 00:00:44,796
Can you give a go for fourth orbit?

4
00:00:44,920 --> 00:00:46,672
Cape Com to Jupiter 16.

5
00:00:46,800 --> 00:00:49,439
Can you confirm 02 pressure
is within limit?

6
00:00:49,560 --> 00:00:53,189
Roger. It all looks good
in the environmental control system.

7
00:00:53,320 --> 00:00:55,834
OK. Everything looks good from here.

8
00:00:55,960 --> 00:00:58,315
You have a go for fourth orbit.

9
00:00:58,440 --> 00:01:00,396
Jupiter 16. Roger.

10
00:01:00,520 --> 00:01:03,910
You're stowing all loose gear.
Ready for the EVA.

11
00:01:04,040 --> 00:01:05,519
Jupiter 16, this is Cape Com.

12
00:01:05,640 --> 00:01:07,437
Start your EVA when you're ready.

13
00:01:07,560 --> 00:01:10,154
You have time in the other EVAs
for experiments.

14
00:01:10,280 --> 00:01:12,236
So don't stay out too long, Chris.

15
00:01:12,360 --> 00:01:13,509
OK, flight.

16
00:01:13,640 --> 00:01:16,598
- Don't worry. We'll stick to plan.
- Roger.

17
00:01:16,720 --> 00:01:21,157
Cape Com to Jupiter 16. On my mark
it will be fourplus three seven.

18
00:01:21,280 --> 00:01:24,078
Four, three, two

19
00:01:24,200 --> 00:01:26,350
one, mark.

20
00:01:32,720 --> 00:01:34,676
Cape Com, this is Chris.

21
00:01:34,800 --> 00:01:36,631
I'm out.

22
00:01:36,760 --> 00:01:38,716
Everything looks OK.

23
00:01:38,840 --> 00:01:40,114
Good.

24
00:01:40,240 --> 00:01:42,515
The manoeuvring unit works this time.

25
00:01:42,640 --> 00:01:45,108
I used it to get out.
It makes things a lot easier.

26
00:01:45,240 --> 00:01:48,198
Cape Com to Hawaii,
this is flight control, come in.

27
00:01:48,320 --> 00:01:49,833
Hawaii, roger.

28
00:01:49,960 --> 00:01:53,589
Hawaii, we expect to start EVA
over your station on this pass.

29
00:01:53,720 --> 00:01:55,199
Hawaii to Jupiter 16.

30
00:01:55,320 --> 00:01:58,517
An unidentified object is closing on you
fast from astern.

31
00:01:58,640 --> 00:01:59,834
Can you see it?

32
00:02:01,000 --> 00:02:04,390
Hawaii, we have nothing here.
Hold while we check the space track.

33
00:02:04,960 --> 00:02:06,678
Hawaii to Jupiter 16.

34
00:02:06,800 --> 00:02:10,429
Repeat, Hawaii to Jupiter 16.

35
00:02:10,560 --> 00:02:12,710
An unidentified object is on our scope.

36
00:02:13,320 --> 00:02:14,833
We see nothing.

37
00:02:15,920 --> 00:02:17,831
Can you give me a bearing?

38
00:02:17,960 --> 00:02:19,473
Appears to be coming up fast,

39
00:02:19,600 --> 00:02:21,431
from astern.

40
00:02:21,560 --> 00:02:23,516
Hey, now I see it.

41
00:02:24,120 --> 00:02:26,076
It's another spacecraft!

42
00:02:26,640 --> 00:02:28,517
Repeat, it's another spacecraft!

43
00:02:28,640 --> 00:02:31,552
Does it looks like a close pass?

44
00:02:31,680 --> 00:02:33,318
You're breaking up. Say again.

45
00:02:33,440 --> 00:02:36,477
- Does it look like a close pass?
- Chris, what's happening?

46
00:02:36,600 --> 00:02:39,558
It's coming right at us.
The front is opening up!

47
00:02:39,680 --> 00:02:42,399
I repeat, the front is opening up!

48
00:02:43,600 --> 00:02:48,116
- It's coming right at us.
- Chris, get back in, get back in!

49
00:02:48,240 --> 00:02:50,549
Do you read me? You're breaking up.

50
00:02:50,680 --> 00:02:53,035
- Repeat, you're breaking up.
- What's happening?

51
00:02:53,160 --> 00:02:55,116
Hawaii to Jupiter 16.

52
00:02:55,840 --> 00:02:58,400
Hawaii to Jupiter 16. Are you receiving?

53
00:02:58,520 --> 00:03:01,080
You're breaking up. Come in, please.
Jupiter 16!

54
00:03:01,200 --> 00:03:03,156
You're breaking up...

55
00:03:09,640 --> 00:03:11,870
My lead line! It's cu...

56
00:03:13,560 --> 00:03:16,916
Hawaii to Jupiter 16, Hawaii to Jupiter 16.

57
00:03:17,040 --> 00:03:20,112
Are you receiving me?
Come in, please. Over.

58
00:03:20,240 --> 00:03:21,389
Hello, Houston.

59
00:03:21,520 --> 00:03:24,478
We've lost radio contact.
We've also lost him on the scope.

60
00:03:24,600 --> 00:03:26,909
Unidentified object is still orbiting.

61
00:03:27,040 --> 00:03:29,873
Alert all stations and track him closely.

62
00:03:39,200 --> 00:03:42,749
It is ridiculous for the Soviet government
to deny responsibility.

63
00:03:42,880 --> 00:03:45,997
The Soviet government denies
all knowledge of this affair.

64
00:03:46,120 --> 00:03:48,634
The world knows
we are a peace-loving people.

65
00:03:48,760 --> 00:03:50,716
I hereby give notice that in 20 days

66
00:03:50,840 --> 00:03:53,400
the United States
will launch her next spaceship.

67
00:03:53,520 --> 00:03:56,592
My government has instructed me
to inform you

68
00:03:56,720 --> 00:04:00,156
that any interference with it
will be regarded as an act of war.

69
00:04:00,280 --> 00:04:01,872
May I ask what motive

70
00:04:02,000 --> 00:04:04,389
our Russian friends would have

71
00:04:04,520 --> 00:04:07,034
for wishing to destroy
American spacecraft?

72
00:04:07,160 --> 00:04:09,674
My government sees this
as a blatant attempt

73
00:04:09,800 --> 00:04:14,112
to gain complete and absolute control
of space itself for military purposes.

74
00:04:14,240 --> 00:04:16,196
We don't agree.

75
00:04:16,320 --> 00:04:18,675
Her Majesty's Government
is not convinced

76
00:04:18,800 --> 00:04:22,031
that this intruder missile
originated from Soviet Russia.

77
00:04:22,160 --> 00:04:24,799
Our tracking station in Singapore

78
00:04:24,920 --> 00:04:29,118
reported faint echoes of this craft
coming down in the Sea of Japan area.

79
00:04:29,240 --> 00:04:32,073
Might I suggest
that this is where you should

80
00:04:32,200 --> 00:04:34,350
concentrate your intelligence forces?

81
00:04:34,480 --> 00:04:38,029
The prime minister asked me to assure
you this is what we propose to do.

82
00:04:38,160 --> 00:04:41,948
As a matter of fact, our man in Hong Kong
is working on it now.

83
00:04:49,680 --> 00:04:53,116
Why do Chinese girls taste different
from all other girls?

84
00:04:53,240 --> 00:04:55,196
You think we better?

85
00:04:55,320 --> 00:04:57,231
No, just different.

86
00:04:57,360 --> 00:04:59,157
Like Peking duck is different from

87
00:04:59,280 --> 00:05:01,475
Russian caviar, but I love 'em both.

88
00:05:01,600 --> 00:05:03,636
Darling, I give you very best duck.

89
00:05:03,760 --> 00:05:05,716
That would be lovely.

90
00:05:05,840 --> 00:05:09,310
We've had some interesting times
together, Ling. I'll be sorry to go.

91
00:05:31,080 --> 00:05:32,752
Take that door.

92
00:05:32,880 --> 00:05:34,836
The bed!

93
00:05:41,440 --> 00:05:44,830
- We're too late.
- At least he died on the job.

94
00:05:45,640 --> 00:05:47,551
He'd have wanted it this way.

95
00:08:48,960 --> 00:08:51,474
We shall not all sleep,
but we shall all be changed

96
00:08:51,600 --> 00:08:54,876
in a moment,
in the twinkling of an eye,

97
00:08:55,000 --> 00:08:56,877
at the last trump.

98
00:08:57,000 --> 00:09:00,709
For the trumpet shall sound and
the dead shall be raised incorruptible,

99
00:09:00,840 --> 00:09:02,796
and we shall all be changed.

100
00:09:02,920 --> 00:09:06,435
We therefore commit his body to the deep
to be turned into corruption,

101
00:09:06,560 --> 00:09:10,519
Iooking for the resurrection of the body
when the sea shall give up her dead.

102
00:09:10,640 --> 00:09:12,517
Present!

103
00:09:14,640 --> 00:09:16,596
Fire!

104
00:09:17,360 --> 00:09:19,316
Fire!

105
00:09:20,280 --> 00:09:22,236
Fire!

106
00:10:30,600 --> 00:10:32,716
- Carry on.
- Aye aye, sir.

107
00:10:51,320 --> 00:10:52,958
Permission to come aboard?

108
00:10:53,080 --> 00:10:55,230
- Permission granted.
- Thank you.

109
00:10:57,680 --> 00:11:00,114
- Take this officer aft.
- Yes, sir.

110
00:11:04,680 --> 00:11:08,036
Number One, take her up to 90ft.
Course zero four five.

111
00:11:08,160 --> 00:11:10,116
Aye aye, sir.

112
00:11:15,440 --> 00:11:18,034
- Hello, Penny.
- You'd better go right in.

113
00:11:18,160 --> 00:11:20,674
You're late as usual,
even from your own funeral.

114
00:11:20,800 --> 00:11:22,756
We corpses have no sense of timing.

115
00:11:24,600 --> 00:11:26,352
In you go... sir.

116
00:11:26,480 --> 00:11:28,436
Thank you... ma'am.

117
00:11:38,320 --> 00:11:41,517
- Sit down, 007.
- Thank you, sir.

118
00:11:42,280 --> 00:11:44,430
- No ill effects?
- None at all, sir.

119
00:11:44,560 --> 00:11:49,429
Now you're dead, perhaps some of your
old friends will pay less attention to you.

120
00:11:49,560 --> 00:11:52,950
Give you more elbow room.
You'll need it, too.

121
00:11:53,080 --> 00:11:57,039
This is the big one, 007. That's why
I'm out here. You're fully briefed?

122
00:11:57,160 --> 00:11:59,594
Yes, but there's one thing
I don't understand.

123
00:11:59,720 --> 00:12:02,359
If our Singapore tracking
station is correct

124
00:12:02,480 --> 00:12:05,631
about the rocket not landing
in Russia, where did it land?

125
00:12:05,760 --> 00:12:08,274
We assume it's Japan.
All this is guesswork,

126
00:12:08,400 --> 00:12:11,437
but the PM wants us to play it
with everything we've got.

127
00:12:11,560 --> 00:12:14,711
- And the aerial reconnaissance?
- All photographed. Nothing.

128
00:12:14,840 --> 00:12:17,400
Are the Japanese equipped
to launch such a rocket?

129
00:12:18,080 --> 00:12:20,196
- We don't think so.
- Then who else is?

130
00:12:20,320 --> 00:12:22,629
That's what you've got to
find out, and fast.

131
00:12:22,760 --> 00:12:24,512
Before the real shooting starts.

132
00:12:24,640 --> 00:12:28,269
This damn thing could blow up
into a full-scale war.

133
00:12:29,240 --> 00:12:32,312
When you get to Tokyo,
go to that name and address.

134
00:12:32,440 --> 00:12:34,590
Our man Henderson
will contact you there.

135
00:12:34,720 --> 00:12:37,871
- Henderson.
- Captain here. Full ahead.

136
00:12:38,000 --> 00:12:39,513
Right.

137
00:12:41,000 --> 00:12:44,197
- That's all.
- Thank you, sir.

138
00:12:44,320 --> 00:12:45,673
- 007.
- Sir?

139
00:12:45,800 --> 00:12:48,439
We've only three weeks
to the next American launch.

140
00:12:48,560 --> 00:12:49,959
- You know that?
- Yes, sir.

141
00:12:50,080 --> 00:12:53,709
My sources tell me the Russians
are planning one even earlier.

142
00:12:53,840 --> 00:12:56,877
- So move fast, 007.
- Yes, sir.

143
00:13:03,560 --> 00:13:05,710
By the way, how was the girl?

144
00:13:06,480 --> 00:13:08,038
Which girl?

145
00:13:08,160 --> 00:13:10,435
The Chinese one we fixed you up with.

146
00:13:10,560 --> 00:13:12,835
Another five minutes, I'd have found out.

147
00:13:12,960 --> 00:13:15,520
She'll never know what she missed.

148
00:13:16,760 --> 00:13:19,718
Miss Moneypenny,
give 007 the password we've agreed

149
00:13:19,840 --> 00:13:22,354
- with Japanese SIS.
- Yes, sir.

150
00:13:22,480 --> 00:13:25,153
We tried to think of something
you wouldn't forget.

151
00:13:25,280 --> 00:13:26,269
Yes?

152
00:13:27,800 --> 00:13:30,519
I... Iove... you.

153
00:13:30,640 --> 00:13:32,790
Repeat it, please,
to make sure you get it.

154
00:13:32,920 --> 00:13:34,478
Don't worry, I get it.

155
00:13:34,600 --> 00:13:36,272
Sayonara.

156
00:13:36,400 --> 00:13:38,550
James... good luck.

157
00:13:40,000 --> 00:13:42,309
Instant Japanese. You may need it.

158
00:13:43,800 --> 00:13:47,110
You forget, I took a first
in oriental languages at Cambridge.

159
00:13:51,520 --> 00:13:53,476
Stand by to load.

160
00:13:56,120 --> 00:13:58,076
Lift to the launch!

161
00:14:02,920 --> 00:14:04,478
Tube loaded.

162
00:14:04,600 --> 00:14:05,510
Hubcap open.

163
00:14:08,960 --> 00:14:10,109
Fire.

164
00:15:52,720 --> 00:15:54,676
This is your ticket.

165
00:15:58,200 --> 00:16:00,156
Thank you.

166
00:16:00,400 --> 00:16:02,356
Dozo.

167
00:17:33,240 --> 00:17:34,878
I love you.

168
00:17:36,520 --> 00:17:38,078
I have a car nearby.

169
00:17:38,200 --> 00:17:41,715
- Where do you suggest we go?
- I know a quiet hotel.

170
00:17:43,920 --> 00:17:47,629
- And?
- Where your friend is waiting.

171
00:17:49,240 --> 00:17:50,719
Mr Henderson.

172
00:17:54,960 --> 00:17:57,155
Wasn't Mr Henderson
able to come himself?

173
00:17:57,280 --> 00:17:59,874
- I suppose not.
- Why?

174
00:18:00,000 --> 00:18:02,116
He didn't say.

175
00:18:16,720 --> 00:18:19,154
I think it's about hotel-time.

176
00:18:44,640 --> 00:18:46,870
How long have you
worked for Henderson?

177
00:18:47,000 --> 00:18:51,039
Long enough to learn not to discuss
such matters with strangers.

178
00:19:09,480 --> 00:19:13,029
- Mr Henderson's waiting for you.
- You're not coming in with me?

179
00:19:13,160 --> 00:19:15,993
Mr Henderson would like
to see you alone.

180
00:19:25,280 --> 00:19:27,236
Do come in.

181
00:19:29,160 --> 00:19:31,116
Mr Henderson?

182
00:19:31,240 --> 00:19:33,196
At your service.

183
00:19:48,640 --> 00:19:51,871
I believe you wanted to
ask me some questions.

184
00:19:52,000 --> 00:19:54,230
Yes. Excuse me.

185
00:19:59,240 --> 00:20:01,708
- Thank you.
- I'm glad you got it right.

186
00:20:02,600 --> 00:20:04,955
I lost that in Singapore in '42.

187
00:20:06,280 --> 00:20:09,192
You must excuse
this rather odd mixture of styles,

188
00:20:09,320 --> 00:20:12,039
but I refuse to go entirely Japanese.

189
00:20:12,160 --> 00:20:15,118
Very fond of some of these old things.

190
00:20:16,360 --> 00:20:19,113
- You've never been to Japan before?
- No, never.

191
00:20:19,240 --> 00:20:22,038
I myself have lived here for...

192
00:20:22,760 --> 00:20:24,716
28 years.

193
00:20:24,840 --> 00:20:27,149
And I'm just beginning
to know my way about.

194
00:20:27,280 --> 00:20:31,432
- Your most vital contact will be Tanaka.
- Tanaka?

195
00:20:31,560 --> 00:20:34,120
He's head of the Japanese secret service.

196
00:20:34,240 --> 00:20:37,755
And his identity is the most
closely guarded secret in Japan.

197
00:20:37,880 --> 00:20:39,836
When can I see him?

198
00:20:40,800 --> 00:20:43,758
- You can see Tiger tonight.
- Tiger?

199
00:20:43,880 --> 00:20:47,316
His closest friends
are permitted to call him that.

200
00:20:47,440 --> 00:20:49,908
- Do you have any leads of your own?
- Yes, I do.

201
00:20:50,040 --> 00:20:52,679
That's stirred not shaken.
That was right?

202
00:20:52,800 --> 00:20:54,358
Perfect.

203
00:20:54,480 --> 00:20:56,436
Cheers.

204
00:20:58,000 --> 00:20:59,956
Russian vodka. Well done.

205
00:21:00,080 --> 00:21:03,436
Yes, I get it from the doorman
at the Russian embassy.

206
00:21:03,560 --> 00:21:05,676
Amongst certain other things.

207
00:21:05,800 --> 00:21:08,030
Now, look. I think London's theory

208
00:21:08,160 --> 00:21:11,516
about the missile being fired
from this country is right.

209
00:21:11,640 --> 00:21:14,074
I don't know how or where.

210
00:21:14,200 --> 00:21:16,555
And don't ask me who's doing it either.

211
00:21:16,680 --> 00:21:22,676
But I have a fairly shrewd idea
that a major foreign power is behind it all.

212
00:21:22,800 --> 00:21:25,360
You mean, apart from Russia and Japan?

213
00:21:25,480 --> 00:21:28,552
It's not Russia, old boy, I'm sure of that.

214
00:21:28,680 --> 00:21:30,636
It's not Japan either.

215
00:21:30,760 --> 00:21:34,878
Although a large Japanese
industrial concern is...

216
00:23:30,440 --> 00:23:32,396
Good evening.

217
00:24:54,680 --> 00:24:56,636
Cheers.

218
00:25:00,720 --> 00:25:02,676
Siamese vodka?

219
00:26:26,160 --> 00:26:28,116
There he is!

220
00:26:36,600 --> 00:26:37,953
Freeze!

221
00:26:54,160 --> 00:26:55,513
Get in, quick!

222
00:27:02,280 --> 00:27:04,396
What the hell's the score?

223
00:27:05,000 --> 00:27:07,560
What do you mean?
My job is to help you.

224
00:27:07,680 --> 00:27:09,636
Like you helped Henderson?

225
00:27:09,760 --> 00:27:11,830
I'm taking you to a place of safety.

226
00:27:11,960 --> 00:27:15,111
No, this time I'm taking you.
I want some information now.

227
00:27:15,240 --> 00:27:19,153
- I have no information to give you.
- We'll see about that. Slow down.

228
00:28:09,400 --> 00:28:11,311
Welcome.

229
00:28:14,960 --> 00:28:16,757
Welcome to Japan, Mr Bond.

230
00:28:17,560 --> 00:28:19,710
It is a great pleasure to meet you at last.

231
00:28:22,280 --> 00:28:24,635
And how do you like our country so far?

232
00:28:27,480 --> 00:28:31,359
I am a trifle disappointed at the ease
with which I could pull you in.

233
00:28:31,480 --> 00:28:34,995
The one thing my honourable mother
taught me long ago

234
00:28:35,120 --> 00:28:37,793
was never to get into a car
with a strange girl.

235
00:28:37,920 --> 00:28:41,799
But you, I'm afraid,
will get into anything with any girl!

236
00:28:45,960 --> 00:28:49,350
You have a lot of energy
for a dead man, Mr Bond.

237
00:28:54,640 --> 00:28:56,596
You are James Bond, aren't you?

238
00:29:01,160 --> 00:29:04,630
I am so very pleased to meet you,
Bond-san. I really am.

239
00:29:05,600 --> 00:29:07,636
Permit me to introduce myself.

240
00:29:07,760 --> 00:29:10,957
My name is Tanaka. Please call me Tiger.

241
00:29:11,080 --> 00:29:14,038
If you're Tanaka,
how do you feel about me?

242
00:29:15,120 --> 00:29:17,270
I... Iove you.

243
00:29:17,400 --> 00:29:19,994
I'm glad we got that out of the way.

244
00:29:20,120 --> 00:29:23,078
I'd like you to examine these
as soon as possible.

245
00:29:23,200 --> 00:29:25,156
They're from Osato's safe.

246
00:29:28,280 --> 00:29:30,350
This is an order for naval stores.

247
00:29:30,480 --> 00:29:34,029
500 kilos of butter, 50 containers of lox.

248
00:29:35,160 --> 00:29:36,878
What is lox?

249
00:29:37,000 --> 00:29:39,560
An American name for smoked salmon.

250
00:29:39,680 --> 00:29:42,638
But it's also the technical name
for liquid oxygen.

251
00:29:42,760 --> 00:29:44,716
Which makes rocket fuel.

252
00:29:44,840 --> 00:29:46,796
- Very interesting.
- Yes.

253
00:29:46,920 --> 00:29:48,672
We must go.

254
00:29:48,800 --> 00:29:51,758
The journey out will be more dignified
than the journey in.

255
00:29:51,880 --> 00:29:53,871
That wouldn't be difficult.

256
